widgets_values:
All of this is to make a more refined very fainted "aura" outline blur mask on the character so the normal inpaint performs better and avoid superposition on denoise. 

Might be completely unecessery for inpainting control-net but I already had this done for another workflow, so why not.

widgets_values: â† If you don't use the "aura" mask, this is where your normal mask "grow with blur" happens. You can tinker with it. This is important to help with blending.
You can use refined "aura" + a final "expand with blur" if you feel like it. This is where you tinker with it. Or just leave this at 0.

inputs.name: ðŸ”§ Image Composite From Mask Batch

widgets_values: â† You should ALWAYS composite at the risk of degrading your whole image if you don't. BUT sometimes you don't care and the image blends better without it, so here it's the option.

This returns the image back to it's original resolution (If it is not a divisiable by 8 resolution) after the wrokflow is done to ensure nothing is changed. 

WARNING:If you are painting the borders, this might give you a border pixel on the right or on the bottom, back form the original image. If you don't want that, you can bypass this group so your final image is a new image with a new resolution that IS divisiable by 8.


IF outpainting is ON this will always be OFF because outpainting will always give you new resolution image that is devisable by 8 and it makes no sense to composite back to the original resolution.

nodes.title: Do a final composite to restore original resolution?

widgets_values:
I decided to add Fill to outpainted areas even if you decide to not use fill to the inpainted areas, because it makes outpainting with different denoise values perform better.

With inpainting, you might want to preserve what is inside the inpainted area with a lower denoise.

For outpainting it makes no sense to preserve a black or gray padded area. So fill always makes sense.

widgets_values: Here it calculates the lowest divisible by 8 resolution and crops the image, taking the extra pixels out. This method instead of resizing is better because the image won't lose any quality, as resizing even by a pixel can damage the original quality. The image will be composited back to the original res at the end of the workflow. (Inpainting ONLY)

nodes.title: Want to preserve the original image prompt and resources?

widgets_values:
Most of the times you don't want to end up with the inpainted prompt and seed recorded to your final inpainted image since the original image composition is normally more important.

So if you want to preserve your original image prompts, LoRas used, seed, CFG, Steps, etc, use these groups.

"Automatic" takes precendent over "Manual" inputs. If you want to input manualy mute the automatic group.

Automatic need you to load/upload your image here again. You still need to load the image on the "Load image and mask" groups

Of course if your image to be inpainted is not AI generated, all these groups to retrieve the old metadata would mean nothing so you can just mute them all.

Want to add any manual models hash? put them here (comma separated AutoV3 hashes).
